Justice Avenue, south side, opposite Fifty-fourth Avenue, showing in there order from fore to background homes owned in 1873 by Mrs. W. Cannon, A. H-----, Mrs. O.M. Malloy (two peaked homes close together in the center of the view), Mrs. Rolls, and Mrs. J.R. Jetens respectively.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Justice Avenue south side, west of Fifty-fourth Avenue, showing in the foreground the home of Mrs. G. M. Maloy in 1873. The house adjoining was that of Mrs. Howard in 1873. The white house was that of Mrs. Ralls and the one beyond and adjoining hers was that of Mrs. Peters. The first, third, and fourth houses mentioned are numbered 30, 26, and 22 respectively.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Justice Avenue, south side, west of Fifty-fourth Avenue, showing in the foreground the first and center houses which belonged to Mrs. Peters in 1873. Beyond the center house are two more peaked roof, which were owned by Mrs. D.J.R. Jetens in 1873.

March 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Justice Ave., west side, north from a point just south of Fifty-fourth Ave. The peaked roof house and that next to it, in the foreground belonged to Mrs. W. Cannon in 1873; the one beyond these two to A. Holt. The last house was that of Mrs. O.M. Mallory. The first three houses in their order had at one time Nos. 50, 36 and 34 respectively. This is a set of two views. The old frame structure and burying grounds of The First Presbyterian Church of Elmhurst may be seen in the background at the left.

January 1923.
View 2: March 1923.

Justice Avenue, north side, partially in the southern street line of Fifty-fourth Avenue, showing four views of the Dr. H. Holt house of 1873. One Thompson was the owner about 1891. This house was still standing in November 1933 and was occupied by Dr. A.C. Combes.

D. J. Patten was the owner in 1852.
